<DOC><DOCNO> AP880504-0314 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1040EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-SouthKorea-USTrade     05-04 0197</FIRST><SECOND>BC-South Korea-US Trade,0202</SECOND><HEAD>US-South Korea Trade Talks Advance</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   South Korea has bowed to U.S. pressureand agreed to remove most restrictions on the sale of importedcigarettes, which could cut their price by 76 percent, tradenegotiators for both countries said Wednesday.   Hwang Doo-yun, chief negotiator for South Korea's Trade-IndustryMinistry, said the two sides also agreed to extend the talks one ortwo days to complete the negotiations on cigarettes, which had beendue to end Wednesday.   Trade officials said South Korea will permit the prices ofimported foreign cigarettes to be lowered from the present $1.76 apack to about $1 a pack beginning in June.   South Korea's domestic brands sell for as much as 81 cents apack.   The talks could not be finished in time because of a U.S. demandthat South Korea permit cigarette advertisements through all newsmedia, the officials said. South Korea has said it would only allowads in magazines.   No major progress was reported in talks on opening the Koreanmarket for U.S. agricultural products. Separate talks would becalled in June to continue discussion on this matter, the officialssaid.</TEXT></DOC>